# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: speech-recognition-ml
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:speech-recognition-ml/connectionist-temporal-classification] The input is a sequence of observations, and the outputs are a sequence of labels, which can include blank outputs.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/connectionist-temporal-classification] The difficulty of training comes from there being many more observations than there are labels.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/connectionist-temporal-classification] For example, in speech audio there can be multiple time slices which correspond to a single phoneme.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/connectionist-temporal-classification] Since we don't know the alignment of the observed sequence with the target labels we predict a probability distribution at each time step.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/connectionist-temporal-classification] A CTC network has a continuous output (e.g. softmax), which is fitted through training to model the probability of a label.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/connectionist-temporal-classification] CTC does not attempt to learn boundaries and timings: Label sequences are considered equivalent if they differ only in alignment, ignoring blanks.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/connectionist-temporal-classification] Equivalent label sequences can occur in many ways – which makes scoring a non-trivial task, but there is an efficient forward–backward algorithm for that.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/connectionist-temporal-classification] CTC scores can then be used with the back-propagation algorithm to update the neural network weights.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/connectionist-temporal-classification] Alternative approaches to a CTC-fitted neural network include a hidden Markov model (HMM).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/connectionist-temporal-classification] In 2009, a Connectionist Temporal Classification (CTC)-trained LSTM network was the first RNN to win pattern recognition contests when it won several competitions in connected handwriting recognition.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/connectionist-temporal-classification] In 2014, the Chinese company Baidu used a bidirectional RNN (not an LSTM) trained on the CTC loss function to break the 2S09 Switchboard Hub5'00 speech recognition dataset benchmark without using any traditional speech processing methods.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/connectionist-temporal-classification] In 2015, it was used in Google voice search and dictation on Android devices.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/connectionist-temporal-classification] CTC is limited to monotonic alignment, which is not a problem for voice recognition, but may be a problem for language translation, as later words in a language A may correspond to earlier words in language B, since the word ordering is different for different languages.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] In probability theory, a **hidden Markov model** (**HMM**) is a Markov model in which the observations are dependent on a latent (or *hidden*) Markov process (referred to as X ).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] An HMM requires that there be an observable process Y whose outcomes depend on the outcomes of X in a known way.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Since X cannot be observed directly, the goal is to learn about state of X by observing Y .
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Estimation of the parameters in an HMM can be performed using maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] For linear chain HMMs, the Baum–Welch algorithm can be used to estimate parameters.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Let $X_{n}$ and $Y_{n}$ be discrete-time stochastic processes and $n\geq 1$ .
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Let $X_{t}$ and $Y_{t}$ be continuous-time stochastic processes.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] In its discrete form, a hidden Markov process can be visualized as a generalization of the urn problem with replacement (where each item from the urn is returned to the original urn before the next step).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] In a room that is not visible to an observer there is a genie.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The room contains urns X1, X2, X3, ... each of which contains a known mix of balls, with each ball having a unique label y1, y2, y3, ... .
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The genie chooses an urn in that room and randomly draws a ball from that urn.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] It then puts the ball onto a conveyor belt, where the observer can observe the sequence of the balls but not the sequence of urns from which they were drawn.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Therefore, this is called a Markov process.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] It can be described by the upper part of Figure 1.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The Markov process cannot be observed, only the sequence of labeled balls, thus this arrangement is called a *hidden Markov process*.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] This is illustrated by the lower part of the diagram shown in Figure 1, where one can see that balls y1, y2, y3, y4 can be drawn at each state.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Even if the observer knows the composition of the urns and has just observed a sequence of three balls, *e.g.* y1, y2 and y3 on the conveyor belt, the observer still cannot be *sure* which urn (*i.e.*, at which state) the genie has drawn the third ball from.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] However, the observer can work out other information, such as the likelihood that the third ball came from each of the urns.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Consider two friends, Alice and Bob, who live far apart from each other and who talk together daily over the telephone about what they did that day.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Bob is only interested in three activities: walking in the park, shopping, and cleaning his apartment.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The choice of what to do is determined exclusively by the weather on a given day.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Alice has no definite information about the weather, but she knows general trends.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Based on what Bob tells her he did each day, Alice tries to guess what the weather must have been like.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Alice believes that the weather operates as a discrete Markov chain.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] There are two states, "Rainy" and "Sunny", but she cannot observe them directly, that is, they are *hidden* from her.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] On each day, there is a certain chance that Bob will perform one of the following activities, depending on the weather: "walk", "shop", or "clean".
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Since Bob tells Alice about his activities, those are the *observations*.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The entire system is that of a hidden Markov model (HMM).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Alice knows the general weather trends in the area, and what Bob likes to do on average.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] In other words, the parameters of the HMM are known.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] In this piece of code, `start_probability` represents Alice's belief about which state the HMM is in when Bob first calls her (all she knows is that it tends to be rainy on average).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The particular probability distribution used here is not the equilibrium one, which is (given the transition probabilities) approximately `{'Rainy': 0.57, 'Sunny': 0.43}`.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The `transition_probability` represents the change of the weather in the underlying Markov chain.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] In this example, there is only a 30% chance that tomorrow will be sunny if today is rainy.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The `emission_probability` represents how likely Bob is to perform a certain activity on each day.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] If it is rainy, there is a 50% chance that he is cleaning his apartment; if it is sunny, there is a 60% chance that he is outside for a walk.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The diagram below shows the general architecture of an instantiated HMM.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Each oval shape represents a random variable that can adopt any of a number of values.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The random variable *x*(*t*) is the hidden state at time t (with the model from the above diagram, *x*(*t*) ∈ {‍*x*1, *x*2, *x*3‍}).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The arrows in the diagram (often called a trellis diagram) denote conditional dependencies.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] From the diagram, it is clear that the conditional probability distribution of the hidden variable *x*(*t*) at time t, given the values of the hidden variable x at all times, depends *only* on the value of the hidden variable *x*(*t* − 1); the values at time *t* − 2 and before have no influence.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Similarly, the value of the observed variable *y*(*t*) depends on only the value of the hidden variable *x*(*t*) (both at time t).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] In the standard type of hidden Markov model considered here, the state space of the hidden variables is discrete, while the observations themselves can either be discrete (typically generated from a categorical distribution) or continuous (typically from a Gaussian distribution).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The parameters of a hidden Markov model are of two types, *transition probabilities* and *emission probabilities* (also known as *output probabilities*).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The transition probabilities control the way the hidden state at time t is chosen given the hidden state at time *t* − 1.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The hidden state space is assumed to consist of one of N possible values, modelled as a categorical distribution.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The set of transition probabilities for transitions from any given state must sum to 1.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Thus, the *N* × *N* matrix of transition probabilities is a Markov matrix.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Because any transition probability can be determined once the others are known, there are a total of *N*(*N* − 1) transition parameters.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] In addition, for each of the N possible states, there is a set of emission probabilities governing the distribution of the observed variable at a particular time given the state of the hidden variable at that time.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The size of this set depends on the nature of the observed variable.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] For example, if the observed variable is discrete with M possible values, governed by a categorical distribution, there will be *M* − 1 separate parameters, for a total of *N*(*M* − 1) emission parameters over all hidden states.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Several inference problems are associated with hidden Markov models, as outlined below.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The task is to compute in a best way, given the parameters of the model, the probability of a particular output sequence.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Applying the principle of dynamic programming, this problem, too, can be handled efficiently using the forward algorithm.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] A number of related tasks ask about the probability of one or more of the latent variables, given the model's parameters and a sequence of observations $y(1),\dots ,y(t)$ .
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The task is to compute, given the model's parameters and a sequence of observations, the distribution over hidden states of the last latent variable at the end of the sequence, i.e. to compute $P(x(t)\mid y(1),\dots ,y(t))$ .
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] This task is used when the sequence of latent variables is thought of as the underlying states that a process moves through at a sequence of points in time, with corresponding observations at each point.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Then, it is natural to ask about the state of the process at the end.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] This problem can be handled efficiently using the forward algorithm.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] An example is when the algorithm is applied to a Hidden Markov Network to determine $\mathrm {P} {\big (}h_{t}\mid v_{1:t}{\big )}$ .
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] This is similar to filtering but asks about the distribution of a latent variable somewhere in the middle of a sequence, i.e. to compute $P(x(k)\mid y(1),\dots ,y(t))$ for some $k<t$ .
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] From the perspective described above, this can be thought of as the probability distribution over hidden states for a point in time *k* in the past, relative to time *t*.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The forward-backward algorithm is a good method for computing the smoothed values for all hidden state variables.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The task, unlike the previous two, asks about the joint probability of the *entire* sequence of hidden states that generated a particular sequence of observations (see illustration on the right).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] This task is generally applicable when HMM's are applied to different sorts of problems from those for which the tasks of filtering and smoothing are applicable.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] An example is part-of-speech tagging, where the hidden states represent the underlying parts of speech corresponding to an observed sequence of words.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] In this case, what is of interest is the entire sequence of parts of speech, rather than simply the part of speech for a single word, as filtering or smoothing would compute.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] This task requires finding a maximum over all possible state sequences, and can be solved efficiently by the Viterbi algorithm.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] For some of the above problems, it may also be interesting to ask about statistical significance.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] What is the probability that a sequence drawn from some null distribution will have an HMM probability (in the case of the forward algorithm) or a maximum state sequence probability (in the case of the Viterbi algorithm) at least as large as that of a particular output sequence?
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] When an HMM is used to evaluate the relevance of a hypothesis for a particular output sequence, the statistical significance indicates the false positive rate associated with failing to reject the hypothesis for the output sequence.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The parameter learning task in HMMs is to find, given an output sequence or a set of such sequences, the best set of state transition and emission probabilities.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The task is usually to derive the maximum likelihood estimate of the parameters of the HMM given the set of output sequences.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] No tractable algorithm is known for solving this problem exactly, but a local maximum likelihood can be derived efficiently using the Baum–Welch algorithm or the Baldi–Chauvin algorithm.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The Baum–Welch algorithm is a special case of the expectation-maximization algorithm.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] If the HMMs are used for time series prediction, more sophisticated Bayesian inference methods, like Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) sampling are proven to be favorable over finding a single maximum likelihood model both in terms of accuracy and stability.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Since MCMC imposes significant computational burden, in cases where computational scalability is also of interest, one may alternatively resort to variational approximations to Bayesian inference, e.g.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Indeed, approximate variational inference offers computational efficiency comparable to expectation-maximization, while yielding an accuracy profile only slightly inferior to exact MCMC-type Bayesian inference.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] HMMs can be applied in many fields where the goal is to recover a data sequence that is not immediately observable (but other data that depend on the sequence are).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Hidden Markov models were described in a series of statistical papers by Leonard E.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Baum and other authors in the second half of the 1960s.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] One of the first applications of HMMs was speech recognition, starting in the mid-1970s.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] From the linguistics point of view, hidden Markov models are equivalent to stochastic regular grammar.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] In the second half of the 1980s, HMMs began to be applied to the analysis of biological sequences, in particular DNA.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Since then, they have become ubiquitous in the field of bioinformatics.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] In the hidden Markov models considered above, the state space of the hidden variables is discrete, while the observations themselves can either be discrete (typically generated from a categorical distribution) or continuous (typically from a Gaussian distribution).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Hidden Markov models can also be generalized to allow continuous state spaces.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Examples of such models are those where the Markov process over hidden variables is a linear dynamical system, with a linear relationship among related variables and where all hidden and observed variables follow a Gaussian distribution.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Nowadays, inference in hidden Markov models is performed in nonparametric settings, where the dependency structure enables identifiability of the model and the learnability limits are still under exploration.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The above algorithms implicitly assume a uniform prior distribution over the transition probabilities.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] However, it is also possible to create hidden Markov models with other types of prior distributions.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] An obvious candidate, given the categorical distribution of the transition probabilities, is the Dirichlet distribution, which is the conjugate prior distribution of the categorical distribution.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Typically, a symmetric Dirichlet distribution is chosen, reflecting ignorance about which states are inherently more likely than others.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The single parameter of this distribution (termed the *concentration parameter*) controls the relative density or sparseness of the resulting transition matrix.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] A choice of 1 yields a uniform distribution.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Values greater than 1 produce a dense matrix, in which the transition probabilities between pairs of states are likely to be nearly equal.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Values less than 1 result in a sparse matrix in which, for each given source state, only a small number of destination states have non-negligible transition probabilities.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] It is also possible to use a two-level prior Dirichlet distribution, in which one Dirichlet distribution (the upper distribution) governs the parameters of another Dirichlet distribution (the lower distribution), which in turn governs the transition probabilities.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The upper distribution governs the overall distribution of states, determining how likely each state is to occur; its concentration parameter determines the density or sparseness of states.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The parameters of models of this sort, with non-uniform prior distributions, can be learned using Gibbs sampling or extended versions of the expectation-maximization algorithm.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] An extension of the previously described hidden Markov models with Dirichlet priors uses a Dirichlet process in place of a Dirichlet distribution.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] This type of model allows for an unknown and potentially infinite number of states.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] It is common to use a two-level Dirichlet process, similar to the previously described model with two levels of Dirichlet distributions.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Such a model is called a *hierarchical Dirichlet process hidden Markov model*, or *HDP-HMM* for short.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] It was originally described under the name "Infinite Hidden Markov Model" and was further formalized in "Hierarchical Dirichlet Processes".
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] A different type of extension uses a discriminative model in place of the generative model of standard HMMs.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] This type of model directly models the conditional distribution of the hidden states given the observations, rather than modeling the joint distribution.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] An example of this model is the so-called *maximum entropy Markov model* (MEMM), which models the conditional distribution of the states using logistic regression (also known as a "maximum entropy model").
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The advantage of this type of model is that arbitrary features (i.e. functions) of the observations can be modeled, allowing domain-specific knowledge of the problem at hand to be injected into the model.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Furthermore, there is no need for these features to be statistically independent of each other, as would be the case if such features were used in a generative model.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Finally, arbitrary features over pairs of adjacent hidden states can be used rather than simple transition probabilities.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The disadvantages of such models are: (1) The types of prior distributions that can be placed on hidden states are severely limited; (2) It is not possible to predict the probability of seeing an arbitrary observation.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] This second limitation is often not an issue in practice, since many common usages of HMM's do not require such predictive probabilities.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] A variant of the previously described discriminative model is the linear-chain conditional random field.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] This uses an undirected graphical model (aka Markov random field) rather than the directed graphical models of MEMM's and similar models.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The advantage of this type of model is that it does not suffer from the so-called *label bias* problem of MEMM's, and thus may make more accurate predictions.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The disadvantage is that training can be slower than for MEMM's.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Yet another variant is the *factorial hidden Markov model*, which allows for a single observation to be conditioned on the corresponding hidden variables of a set of K independent Markov chains, rather than a single Markov chain.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] It is equivalent to a single HMM, with $N^{K}$ states (assuming there are N states for each chain), and therefore, learning in such a model is difficult: for a sequence of length T , a straightforward Viterbi algorithm has complexity $O(N^{2K}\,T)$ .
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] To find an exact solution, a junction tree algorithm could be used, but it results in an $O(N^{K+1}\,K\,T)$ complexity.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] In practice, approximate techniques, such as variational approaches, could be used.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The disadvantage of such models is that dynamic-programming algorithms for training them have an $O(N^{K}\,T)$ running time, for K adjacent states and T total observations (i.e. a length- T Markov chain).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] This extension has been widely used in bioinformatics, in the modeling of DNA sequences.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Another recent extension is the *triplet Markov model*, in which an auxiliary underlying process is added to model some data specificities.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Many variants of this model have been proposed.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] One should also mention the interesting link that has been established between the *theory of evidence* and the *triplet Markov models* and which allows to fuse data in Markovian context and to model nonstationary data.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Finally, a different rationale towards addressing the problem of modeling nonstationary data by means of hidden Markov models was suggested in 2012.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] It consists in employing a small recurrent neural network (RNN), specifically a reservoir network, to capture the evolution of the temporal dynamics in the observed data.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] This information, encoded in the form of a high-dimensional vector, is used as a conditioning variable of the HMM state transition probabilities.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Under such a setup, eventually is obtained a nonstationary HMM, the transition probabilities of which evolve over time in a manner that is inferred from the data, in contrast to some unrealistic ad-hoc model of temporal evolution.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] In 2023, two innovative algorithms were introduced for the Hidden Markov Model.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] These algorithms enable the computation of the posterior distribution of the HMM without the necessity of explicitly modeling the joint distribution, utilizing only the conditional distributions.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Unlike traditional methods such as the Forward-Backward and Viterbi algorithms, which require knowledge of the joint law of the HMM and can be computationally intensive to learn, the Discriminative Forward-Backward and Discriminative Viterbi algorithms circumvent the need for the observation's law.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] This breakthrough allows the HMM to be applied as a discriminative model, offering a more efficient and versatile approach to leveraging Hidden Markov Models in various applications.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The model suitable in the context of longitudinal data is named latent Markov model.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The basic version of this model has been extended to include individual covariates, random effects and to model more complex data structures such as multilevel data.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Given a Markov transition matrix and an invariant distribution on the states, a probability measure can be imposed on the set of subshifts.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] For example, consider the Markov chain given on the right on the states $A,B_{1},B_{2}$ , with invariant distribution $\pi =(2/7,4/7,1/7)$ .
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] By ignoring the distinction between $B_{1},B_{2}$ , this space of subshifts is projected on $A,B_{1},B_{2}$ into another space of subshifts on $A,B$ , and this projection also projects the probability measure down to a probability measure on the subshifts on $A,B$ .
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] The curious thing is that the probability measure on the subshifts on $A,B$ is not created by a Markov chain on $A,B$ , not even multiple orders.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Intuitively, this is because if one observes a long sequence of $B^{n}$ , then one would become increasingly sure that the $\Pr(A\mid B^{n})\to {\frac {2}{3}}$ , meaning that the observable part of the system can be affected by something infinitely in the past.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/hidden-markov-model] Conversely, there exists a space of subshifts on 6 symbols, projected to subshifts on 2 symbols, such that any Markov measure on the smaller subshift has a preimage measure that is not Markov of any order (example 2.6).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] In sound processing, the **mel-frequency cepstrum** (**MFC**) is a representation of the short-term power spectrum of a sound, based on a linear cosine transform of a log power spectrum on a nonlinear mel scale of frequency.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Map the powers of the spectrum obtained above onto the mel scale, using triangular overlapping windows or alternatively, cosine overlapping windows.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Take the logs of the powers at each of the mel frequencies.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Take the discrete cosine transform of the list of mel log powers, as if it were a signal.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] The MFCCs are the amplitudes of the resulting spectrum.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] There can be variations on this process, for example: differences in the shape or spacing of the windows used to map the scale, or addition of dynamics features such as "delta" and "delta-delta" (first- and second-order frame-to-frame difference) coefficients.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] The European Telecommunications Standards Institute in the early 2000s defined a standardised MFCC algorithm to be used in mobile phones.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] MFCCs are commonly used as features in speech recognition systems, such as the systems which can automatically recognize numbers spoken into a telephone.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] MFCCs are also increasingly finding uses in music information retrieval applications such as genre classification, audio similarity measures, etc.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Since Mel-frequency bands are distributed evenly in MFCC, and they are very similar to the voice system of a human, MFCC can efficiently be used to characterize speakers.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] For instance, it can be used to recognize the speaker's cell phone model characteristics, and further the details of the speaker's voice.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] This type of mobile device recognition is possible because the production of electronic components in a phone have tolerances, because different electronic circuit realizations do not have exact same transfer functions.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] The dissimilarities in the transfer function from one realization to another becomes more prominent if the task performing circuits are from different manufacturers.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Hence, each cell phone introduces a convolutional distortion on input speech that leaves its unique impact on the recordings from the cell phone.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Therefore, a particular phone can be identified from the recorded speech by multiplying the original frequency spectrum with further multiplications of transfer functions specific to each phone followed by signal processing techniques.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Thus, by using MFCC one can characterize cell phone recordings to identify the brand and model of the phone.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] As speech is not stationary signal, it is divided into overlapped frames within which the signal is assumed to be stationary.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] where *w(n)*: windowed function of length W.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Hence, as specified the footprint of mobile phone of the recorded speech is the convolution distortion that helps to identify the recording phone.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] $H(f)$ can be considered as a concatenated transfer function that produced input speech, and the recorded speech $Y_{p}w(f)$ can be perceived as original speech from cell phone.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] So, equivalent transfer function of vocal tract and cell phone recorder is considered as original source of recorded speech.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] where *Xew(f)* is the excitation function, $X_{v}(f)$ is the vocal tract transfer function for speech in the $p^{th}$ frame and $H'(f)$ is the equivalent transfer function that characterizes the cell phone.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] This approach can be useful for speaker recognition as the device identification and the speaker identification are very much connected.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] MFCC is successful because of this nonlinear transformation with additive property.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] where, cy(j), ce(j), cw(j) are the recorded speech cepstrum and weighted equivalent impulse response of cell phone recorder that characterizes the cell phone, respectively, while j is the number of filters in the filter bank.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] More precisely, the device specific information is in the recorded speech which is converted to additive form suitable for identification.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] cy(j) can be further processed for identification of the recording phone.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Commonly used window functions- Hamming and Hanning windows.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Hence, Mel-scale is a commonly used frequency scale that is linear till 1000 Hz and logarithmic above it.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] MFCCs are obtained by taking Discrete Cosine Transform (DCT) of the spectral envelope.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] where $c_{i}=c_{y}(i)$ corresponds to the i -th MFCC coefficient, $N_{f}$ is the number of triangular filters in the filter bank, $S_{n}$ is the log energy output of n -th filter coefficient, and L is the number of MFCC coefficients that we want to calculate.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Each step corresponds to one step in MFCC calculation.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] MFCC values are not very robust in the presence of additive noise, and so it is common to normalise their values in speech recognition systems to lessen the influence of noise.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Some researchers propose modifications to the basic MFCC algorithm to improve robustness, such as by raising the log-mel-amplitudes to a suitable power (around 2 or 3) before taking the discrete cosine transform (DCT), which reduces the influence of low-energy components.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Paul Mermelstein is typically credited with the development of the MFC.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Sometimes both early originators are cited.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Many authors, including Davis and Mermelstein, have commented that the spectral basis functions of the cosine transform in the MFC are very similar to the principal components of the log spectra, which were applied to speech representation and recognition much earlier by Pols and his colleagues.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] A **spectrogram** is a visual representation of the spectrum of frequencies of a signal as it varies with time.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] When applied to an audio signal, spectrograms are sometimes called **sonographs**, **voiceprints**, or **voicegrams**.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] When the data are represented in a 3D plot they may be called *waterfall displays*.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] Spectrograms are used extensively in the fields of music, linguistics, sonar, radar, speech processing, seismology, ornithology, and others.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] Spectrograms of audio can be used to identify spoken words phonetically, and to analyse the various calls of animals.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] A spectrogram can be generated by an optical spectrometer, a bank of band-pass filters, by Fourier transform or by a wavelet transform (in which case it is also known as a **scaleogram** or **scalogram**).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] A spectrogram is usually depicted as a heat map, i.e., as an image with the intensity shown by varying the colour or brightness.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] A common format is a graph with two geometric dimensions: one axis represents time, and the other axis represents frequency; a third dimension indicating the amplitude of a particular frequency at a particular time is represented by the intensity or color of each point in the image.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] There are many variations of format: sometimes the vertical and horizontal axes are switched, so time runs up and down; sometimes as a waterfall plot where the amplitude is represented by height of a 3D surface instead of color or intensity.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] The frequency and amplitude axes can be either linear or logarithmic, depending on what the graph is being used for.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] Audio would usually be represented with a logarithmic amplitude axis (probably in decibels, or dB), and frequency would be linear to emphasize harmonic relationships, or logarithmic to emphasize musical, tonal relationships.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] Spectrograms of light may be created directly using an optical spectrometer over time.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] Spectrograms may be created from a time-domain signal in one of two ways: approximated as a filterbank that results from a series of band-pass filters (this was the only way before the advent of modern digital signal processing), or calculated from the time signal using the Fourier transform.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] These two methods actually form two different time–frequency representations, but are equivalent under some conditions.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] The bandpass filters method usually uses analog processing to divide the input signal into frequency bands; the magnitude of each filter's output controls a transducer that records the spectrogram as an image on paper.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] Creating a spectrogram using the FFT is a digital process.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] Digitally sampled data, in the time domain, is broken up into chunks, which usually overlap, and Fourier transformed to calculate the magnitude of the frequency spectrum for each chunk.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] Each chunk then corresponds to a vertical line in the image; a measurement of magnitude versus frequency for a specific moment in time (the midpoint of the chunk).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] These spectrums or time plots are then "laid side by side" to form the image or a three-dimensional surface, or slightly overlapped in various ways, i.e. windowing.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] This process essentially corresponds to computing the squared magnitude of the short-time Fourier transform (STFT) of the signal $s(t)$ — that is, for a window width $\omega$ , $\mathrm {spectrogram} (t,\omega )=\left|\mathrm {STFT} (t,\omega )\right|^{2}$ .
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] From the formula above, it appears that a spectrogram contains no information about the exact, or even approximate, phase of the signal that it represents.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] For this reason, it is not possible to reverse the process and generate a copy of the original signal from a spectrogram, though in situations where the exact initial phase is unimportant it may be possible to generate a useful approximation of the original signal.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] The Analysis & Resynthesis Sound Spectrograph is an example of a computer program that attempts to do this.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] The pattern playback was an early speech synthesizer, designed at Haskins Laboratories in the late 1940s, that converted pictures of the acoustic patterns of speech (spectrograms) back into sound.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] In fact, there is some phase information in the spectrogram, but it appears in another form, as time delay (or group delay) which is the dual of the instantaneous frequency.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] The size and shape of the analysis window can be varied.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] A smaller (shorter) window will produce more accurate results in timing, at the expense of precision of frequency representation.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] A larger (longer) window will provide a more precise frequency representation, at the expense of precision in timing representation.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/spectrogram] This is an instance of the Heisenberg uncertainty principle, that the product of the precision in two conjugate variables is greater than or equal to a constant (B*T>=1 in the usual notation).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Speech recognition applications include voice user interfaces, where the user speaks to a device, which "listens" and processes the audio.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Common voice applications include interpreting commands for calling, call routing, home automation, and aircraft control.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] These applications are called direct voice input.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Productivity applications include searching audio recordings, creating transcripts, and dictation.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Speech recognition can be used to analyse speaker characteristics, such as identifying native language using pronunciation assessment.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Voice recognition (speaker identification) refers to identifying the speaker, rather than speech contents.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Recognizing the speaker can simplify the task of translating speech in systems trained on a specific person's voice.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] It can also be used to authenticate the speaker as part of a security process.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Applications for speech recognition developed over many decades, with progress accelerated due to advances in deep learning and the use of big data.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] These advances are reflected in an increase in academic papers, and greater system adoption.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Key areas of growth include vocabulary size, more accurate recognition for unfamiliar speakers (speaker independence), and faster processing speed.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Raj Reddy was the first person to work on continuous speech recognition, as a graduate student at Stanford University in the late 1960s.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Previous systems required users to pause after each word.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Reddy's system issued spoken commands for playing chess.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Around this time, Soviet researchers invented the dynamic time warping (DTW) algorithm and used it to create a recognizer capable of operating on a 200-word vocabulary.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] DTW processed speech by dividing it into short frames (e.g.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] 10 ms segments) and treating each frame as a unit.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Speaker independence, however, remained unsolved.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] During the late 1960s, Leonard Baum developed the mathematics of Markov chains at the Institute for Defense Analysis.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] A decade later, at CMU, Raj Reddy's students James Baker and Janet M.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Baker began using the hidden Markov model (HMM) for speech recognition.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] James Baker had learned about HMMs while at the Institute for Defense Analysis.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] HMMs enabled researchers to combine sources of knowledge, such as acoustics, language, and syntax, in a unified probabilistic model.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] By the mid-1980s, Fred Jelinek's team at IBM created a voice-activated typewriter called Tangora, which could handle a 20,000-word vocabulary.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Jelinek's statistical approach placed less emphasis on emulating human brain processes in favor of statistical modelling.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] (Jelinek's group independently discovered the application of HMMs to speech.) This was controversial among linguists since HMMs are too simplistic to account for many features of human languages.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] However, the HMM proved to be a highly useful way for modelling speech and replaced dynamic time warping as the dominant speech recognition algorithm in the 1980s.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The 1980s also saw the introduction of the n-gram language model.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] At the end of the DARPA program in 1976, the best computer available to researchers was the PDP-10 with 4 MB of RAM.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] It could take up to 100 minutes to decode 30 seconds of speech.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] By the early 1990s, the vocabulary of the typical commercial speech recognition system had exceeded the average human vocabulary.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Reddy's former student, Xuedong Huang, developed the Sphinx-II system at CMU.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Sphinx-II was the first to do speaker-independent, large vocabulary, continuous speech recognition, and it won DARPA's 1992 evaluation.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Handling continuous speech with a large vocabulary was a major milestone.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Huang later founded the speech recognition group at Microsoft in 1993.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Reddy's student Kai-Fu Lee joined Apple, where, in 1992, he helped develop the Casper speech interface prototype.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Lernout & Hauspie, a Belgium-based speech recognition company, acquired other companies, including Kurzweil Applied Intelligence in 1997 and Dragon Systems in 2000.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] L&H was an industry leader until an accounting scandal destroyed it in 2001.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] L&H speech technology was bought by ScanSoft, which became Nuance in 2005.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Apple licensed Nuance software for its digital assistant Siri.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In the 2000s, DARPA sponsored two speech recognition programs: Effective Affordable Reusable Speech-to-Text (EARS) in 2002, followed by Global Autonomous Language Exploitation (GALE) in 2005.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Four teams participated in EARS: IBM; a team led by BBN with LIMSI and the University of Pittsburgh; Cambridge University; and a team composed of ICSI, SRI, and the University of Washington.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] EARS funded the collection of the Switchboard telephone speech corpus, which contained 260 hours of recorded conversations from over 500 speakers.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The GALE program focused on Arabic and Mandarin broadcast news.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Google's first effort at speech recognition came in 2007 after recruiting Nuance researchers.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Its first product, GOOG-411, was a telephone-based directory service.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] National Security Agency has employed keyword spotting, allowing analysts to index large volumes of recorded conversations and identify speech containing "interesting" keywords.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Other government research programs focused on intelligence applications, such as DARPA's EARS program and IARPA's Babel program.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In the early 2000s, speech recognition was dominated by hidden Markov models combined with feed-forward artificial neural networks (ANN).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Later, speech recognition was taken over by long short-term memory (LSTM), a recurrent neural network (RNN) published by Sepp Hochreiter & Jürgen Schmidhuber in 1997.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] LSTM RNNs avoid the vanishing gradient problem and can learn "Very Deep Learning" tasks that require memories of events that happened thousands of discrete time steps earlier, which is important for speech.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Around 2007, LSTMs trained with Connectionist Temporal Classification (CTC) began to outperform.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In 2015, Google reported a 49 percent error‑rate reduction in its speech recognition via CTC‑trained LSTM.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Transformers, a type of neural network based solely on attention, were adopted in computer vision and language modelling, and then to speech recognition.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Deep feed-forward (non-recurrent) networks for acoustic modelling were introduced in 2009 by Geoffrey Hinton and his students at the University of Toronto, and by Li Deng and colleagues at Microsoft Research.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In contrast to the prioer incremental improvements, deep learning decreased error rates by 30%.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Both shallow and deep forms (e.g., recurrent nets) of ANNs had been explored since the 1980s.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] However, these methods never defeated non-uniform internal-handcrafting Gaussian mixture model/hidden Markov model (GMM-HMM) technology.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Difficulties analyzed in the 1990s, included gradient diminishing and weak temporal correlation structure.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] All these difficulties combined with insufficient training data and computing power.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Most speech recognition pursued generative modelling approaches until deep learning won the day.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] By early the 2010s, speech recognition was differentiated from speaker recognition, and speaker independence was considered a major breakthrough.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Until then, systems required a "training" period for each voice.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In 2017, Microsoft researchers reached the human parity milestone of transcribing conversational speech on the widely benchmarked Switchboard task.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Multiple deep learning models were used to improve accuracy.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The error rate was reported to be as low as 4 professional human transcribers working together on the same benchmark.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Both acoustic modeling and language modeling are important parts of statistically-based speech recognition algorithms.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Hidden Markov models (HMMs) are widely used in many systems.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Language modelling is also used in many other natural language processing applications, such as document classification or statistical machine translation.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Speech recognition systems are based on HMMs.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] These are statistical models that output a sequence of symbols or quantities.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] HMMs are used in speech recognition because a speech signal can be viewed as a piecewise stationary signal or a short-time stationary signal.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] 10 milliseconds), speech can be approximated as a stationary process.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Speech can be thought of as a Markov model for many stochastic purposes.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] HMMs are popular because they can be trained automatically and are simple and computationally feasible.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] An HMM outputs a sequence of *n*-dimensional real-valued vectors (where *n* is an integer such as 10), outputting one every 10 milliseconds.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The vectors consist of cepstral coefficients, obtained by a Fourier transform of a short window of speech and decorrelating the spectrum using a cosine transform, then taking the first (most significant) coefficients.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The HMM tends to have, in each state, a statistical distribution that is a mixture of diagonal covariance Gaussians, which give a likelihood for each observed vector.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Each word, or (for more general speech recognition systems), each phoneme, has a different output distribution; an HMM for a sequence of words or phonemes is made by concatenating the individual trained HMMs for the separate words and phonemes.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Speech recognition systems use combinations of standard techniques to improve results.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] A typical large-vocabulary system applies context dependency for the phonemes (so that phonemes with different left and right context have different realizations as HMM states).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] It uses cepstral normalization to handle speaker and recording conditions.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] It might use vocal tract length normalization (VTLN) for male-female normalization and maximum likelihood linear regression (MLLR) for more general adaptation.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Many systems use discriminative training techniques that dispense with a purely statistical approach to HMM parameter estimation and instead optimize some classification-related measure of the training data.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Examples are maximum mutual information (MMI), minimum classification error (MCE), and minimum phone error (MPE).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Dynamic time warping was historically used for speech recognition, but was later displaced by HMM.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Dynamic time warping measures similarity between two sequences that may vary in time or speed.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] For instance, similarities in walking patterns could be detected, even if in one video a person was walking slowly and in another was walking more quickly, or even if accelerations and decelerations came during one observation.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] DTW has been applied to video, audio, and graphics – any data that can be turned into a linear representation can be analyzed with DTW.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] This could handle speech at different speaking speeds.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In general, it allows an optimal match between two sequences (e.g., time series) with certain restrictions.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The sequences are "warped" non-linearly to match each other.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] This sequence alignment method is often used in the context of HMMs.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Neural networks became interesting in the late 1980s before beginning to dominate in the 2010s.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Neural networks have been used in many aspects of speech recognition, such as phoneme classification, phoneme classification through multi-objective evolutionary algorithms, isolated word recognition, audiovisual speech recognition, audiovisual speaker recognition, and speaker adaptation.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Neural networks make fewer explicit assumptions about feature statistical properties than HMMs.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] When used to estimate the probabilities of a speech segment, neural networks allow natural and efficient discriminative training.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] However, in spite of their effectiveness in classifying short-time units such as individual phonemes and isolated words, early neural networks were rarely successful for continuous recognition because of their limited ability to model temporal dependencies.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] One approach was to use neural networks for feature transformation, or dimensionality reduction.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] However, more recently, LSTM and related recurrent neural networks (RNNs), Time Delay Neural Networks (TDNN's), and transformers demonstrated improved performance.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Researchers are exploring deep neural networks (DNNs) and denoising autoencoders.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] A DNN is a type of artificial neural network that includes multiple hidden layers between the input and output.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Like simpler neural networks, DNNs can model complex, non-linear relationships.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] However, their deeper architecture allows them to build more sophisticated representations that combine features from earlier layers.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] This gives them a powerful ability to learn and recognize complex patterns in speech data.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] A major breakthrough in using DNNs for large vocabulary speech recognition came in 2010.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In a collaboration between industry and academia, researchers used DNNs with large output layers based on context-dependent HMM states that were created using decision trees.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] This approach significantly improved performance.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] A core idea behind deep learning is to eliminate the need for manually designed features and instead learn directly from input data.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] This was first demonstrated using deep autoencoders trained on raw spectrograms or linear filter-bank features.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] These models outperformed traditional Mel-Cepstral features, which rely on fixed transformations.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] More recently, researchers showed that waveforms can achieve excellent results in large-scale speech recognition.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Since 2014, much research has considered "end-to-end" ASR.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Traditional phonetic-based (i.e., all HMM-based model) approaches required separate components and training for pronunciation, acoustic, and language.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] End-to-end models learn from all the components at once.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] This simplifies the training and deployment processes.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] For example, an n-gram language model is required for all HMM-based systems, and a typical 2025-era n-gram language model often takes gigabytes in memory, making them impractical to deploy on mobile devices.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Consequently, ASR systems from Google and Apple (as of 2017) deploy on servers and required a network connection to operate.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The first attempt at end-to-end ASR was the Connectionist Temporal Classification (CTC)-based system introduced by Alex Graves of Google DeepMind and Navdeep Jaitly of the University of Toronto in 2014.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The model consisted of RNNs and a CTC layer.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Jointly, the RNN-CTC model learns the pronunciation and acoustic model together, however, it is incapable of learning the language model due to conditional independence assumptions, similar to an HMM.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Consequently, CTC models can directly learn to map speech acoustics to English characters, but the models make many common spelling mistakes and must rely on a separate language model to finalize transcripts.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Later, Baidu expanded on the work with extremely large datasets and demonstrated some commercial success in Mandarin and English.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In 2016, the University of Oxford presented LipNet, the first end-to-end sentence-level lipreading model, using spatiotemporal convolutions coupled with an RNN-CTC architecture, surpassing human-level performance in a restricted dataset.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] A large-scale convolutional-RNN-CTC architecture was presented in 2018 by Google DeepMind, achieving 6 times better performance than human experts.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In 2019, Nvidia launched two CNN-CTC ASR models, Jasper and QuarzNet, with an overall performance word error rate (WER) of 3%.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Similar to other deep learning applications, transfer learning and domain adaptation are important strategies for reusing and extending the capabilities of deep learning models, particularly due to the small size of available corpora in many languages and/or specific domains.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In 2018, researchers at MIT Media Lab announced preliminary work on AlterEgo, a device that uses electrodes to read the neuromuscular signals users make as they subvocalize.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] They trained a convolutional neural network to translate the electrode signals into words.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Attention-based ASR models were introduced by Chan et al. of Carnegie Mellon University and Google Brain, and Bahdanau et al. of the University of Montreal in 2016.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The model named "Listen, Attend and Spell" (LAS), literally "listens" to the acoustic signal, pays "attention" to all parts of the signal and "spells" out the transcript one character at a time.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Unlike CTC-based models, attention-based models require conditional-independence assumptions and can learn all the components of a speech recognizer directly.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] This means that during deployment, no *a priori* language model is required, making it less demanding for applications with limited memory.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Attention-based models immediately outperformed CTC models (with or without an external language model) and continued improving.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Latent Sequence Decomposition (LSD) was proposed by Carnegie Mellon University, MIT, and Google Brain to directly emit sub-word units that are more natural than English characters.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The University of Oxford and Google DeepMind extended LAS to "Watch, Listen, Attend and Spell" (WLAS) to handle lip reading and surpassed human-level performance.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Voice commands may be used to initiate phone calls, select radio stations, or play music.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Voice recognition capabilities vary across car make and model.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Some models offer natural-language speech recognition, allowing the driver to use full sentences and common phrases in a conversational style.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] With such systems, fixed commands are not required.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Automatic pronunciation assessment is the use of speech recognition to verify the correctness of speech, as distinguished from assessment by a person.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Pronunciation assessment does not determine unknown speech (as in dictation or automatic transcription) but instead, compares speech to a reference model for the words spoken, sometimes with inconsequential prosody such as intonation, pitch, tempo, rhythm, and stress.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Pronunciation assessment is also used in reading tutoring, for example in products such as Microsoft Teams and Amira Learning.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Pronunciation assessment can also be used to help diagnose and treat speech disorders such as apraxia.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Assessing intelligibility is essential for avoiding inaccuracies from accent bias, especially in high-stakes assessments, from words with multiple correct pronunciations, and from phoneme coding errors in digital pronunciation dictionaries.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In 2022, researchers found that some newer speech to text systems, based on end-to-end reinforcement learning to map audio signals directly into words, produce word and phrase confidence scores closely correlated with listener intelligibility.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In the Common European Framework of Reference for Languages (CEFR) assessment criteria for "overall phonological control", intelligibility outweighs formally correct pronunciation at all levels.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In the health care sector, speech recognition can be implemented in front-end or back-end medical documentation processes.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In front-end speech recognition, the provider dictates into a speech-recognition engine, words are displayed as they are recognized, and the speaker is responsible for editing and signing off on the document.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In back-end or deferred speech recognition the provider speaks into a digital dictation system, the voice is routed through a speech-recognition machine, and a draft document is routed along with the voice file to an editor, who edits/finalizes the draft and final report.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] A major issue is that the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009 (ARRA) provides substantial financial benefits to physicians who utilize an Electronic Health Record (EHR) that complies with "Meaningful Use" standards.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] These standards require that substantial data be maintained by the EHR.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] A more significant issue is that most EHRs have not been expressly tailored to take advantage of voice-recognition capabilities.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] A large part of a clinician's interaction with EHR involves navigation through the user interface that is heavily dependent on keyboard and mouse; voice-based navigation provides only modest ergonomic benefits.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Prolonged use of speech recognition software in conjunction with word processors has shown benefits to short-term-memory restrengthening in brain AVM patients who have been treated with resection.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Further research needs to be conducted to determine cognitive benefits for individuals whose AVMs have been treated using radiologic techniques.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Substantial efforts have been devoted to the test and evaluation of speech recognition in fighter aircraft.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Of particular note have been the US programme in speech recognition for the Advanced Fighter Technology Integration (AFTI)/F-16 aircraft (F-16 VISTA), the programme in France for Mirage aircraft, and UK programmes dealing with a variety of aircraft platforms.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In these programmes, speech recognizers have been operated successfully, with applications including setting radio frequencies, commanding an autopilot system, setting steer-point coordinates and weapons release parameters, and controlling flight display.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Working with Swedish pilots flying the JAS-39 Gripen, Englund (2004) reported that recognition deteriorated with increasing g-loads.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The study concluded that adaptation greatly improved the results in all cases and that the introduction of models for breathing was shown to improve recognition scores significantly.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Contrary to what might have been expected, no effects of the broken English of the speakers were found.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Spontaneous speech caused problems for the recognizer, as might have been expected.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] A restricted vocabulary, and above all, a proper syntax, could thus be expected to improve recognition accuracy substantially.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The Eurofighter Typhoon employs a speaker-dependent system, requiring each pilot to create a template.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The system is not used for safety-critical or weapon-critical tasks, such as weapon release or lowering of the undercarriage, but is used for many cockpit functions.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Voice commands are confirmed by visual and/or aural feedback.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The system is seen as a major benefit in the reduction of pilot workload, and allows the pilot to assign targets with two voice commands or to a wingman with only five commands.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Speaker-independent systems are under test for the F-35 Lightning II (JSF) and the Alenia Aermacchi M-346 Master lead-in fighter trainer.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] These systems have produced word accuracy scores in excess of 98%.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The problems of achieving high recognition accuracy under stress and noise are particularly relevant in the helicopter environment as well as in the fighter environment.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The acoustic noise problem is actually more severe in the helicopter environment, because of the high noise levels, and because helicopter pilots, in general, do not wear a facemask, which would reduce acoustic noise in the microphone.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Substantial test and evaluation programmes, notably by the U.S.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Army Avionics Research and Development Activity (AVRADA) and by the Royal Aerospace Establishment (RAE) in the UK.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Work in France included speech recognition in the Puma helicopter.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Voice applications include control of communication radios, navigation systems, and an automated target handover system.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The overriding issue for voice is the impact on pilot effectiveness.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Encouraging results are reported for the AVRADA tests, although these represent only a feasibility demonstration in a test environment.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Much remains to be done both in speech recognition and in overall speech technology in order to consistently achieve performance improvements in operational settings.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Training for air traffic controllers (ATC) represents an excellent application for speech recognition systems.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Many ATC training systems currently require a trainer to act as a "pseudo-pilot", engaging in a voice dialog with the trainee controller, which simulates the dialog that the controller would have with real pilots.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Speech recognition and synthesis techniques offer the potential to eliminate the need for a person to act as a pseudo-pilot, thus reducing training and support personnel.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In theory, air controller tasks are characterized by highly structured speech as the primary output, reducing the difficulty of the speech recognition task.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] FAA document 7110.65 details the phrases that should be used by air traffic controllers.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] While this document gives less than 150 examples of such phrases, the number of phrases supported by one of the simulation vendors speech recognition systems is in excess of 500,000.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The USAF, USMC, US Army, US Navy, and FAA as well as international ATC training organizations such as the Royal Australian Air Force and Civil Aviation Authorities in Italy, Brazil, and Canada use ATC simulators with speech recognition.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Speech recognition programs can provide many benefit to those with disabilities.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] For individuals who are deaf or hard of hearing, speech recognition software can be used to generate captions of conversations.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Additionally, individuals who are blind (see blindness and education) or have poor vision can benefit from listening to textual content, as well as garner more functionality from a computer by issuing commands with their voice.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The use of voice recognition software, in conjunction with a digital audio recorder and a personal computer running word-processing software, has proven useful for restoring damaged short-term memory capacity in individuals who have suffered a stroke or have undergone a craniotomy.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Speech recognition has proven very useful for those who have difficulty using their hands due to causes ranging from mild repetitive stress injuries to disabilities that preclude the use of conventional computer input devices.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Individuals with physical disabilities can use voice commands and transcription to navigate electronics hands-free.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In fact, people who developed RSI from keyboard use became an early and urgent market for speech recognition.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Speech recognition is used in deaf telephony, such as voicemail to text, relay services, and captioned telephone.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Individuals with learning disabilities who struggle with thought-to-paper communication may benefit from the software, but the product's fallibility remains a significant consideration for many.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In addition, speech to text technology is only an effective aid for those with intellectual disabilities if the proper training and resources are provided (e.g. in the classroom setting).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] This type of technology can help those with dyslexia and other learning disabilities.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Speech-to-text has been found to improve the writing quality of students with learning disabilities.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] When compared to handwriting samples, students with learning disabilities who used speech-to-text were found to write faster and to have longer, more complex sentences with less errors.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Self esteem of young students with learning disabilities was found to rise when using speech to text due to decreased levels of anxiety associated with writing.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Students make less mistakes when using the software compared to handwriting which makes them more confident in their writing.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Mistakes made by the software hinder its effectiveness, since misheard words take more time to fix.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The act of having to go back and revise misheard words helps students to see and fix their mistakes.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] This has been shown to increase error recognition skills for users.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] ASR is now commonplace in the field of telephony.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In telephony systems, ASR is predominantly used in contact centers by integrating it with IVR systems.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] It is becoming more widespread in computer gaming and simulation.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Despite the high level of integration with word processing in general personal computing, in the field of document production, ASR has not seen the expected increases in use.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The improvement of mobile processor speeds has made speech recognition practical in smartphones.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Speech is used mostly as a part of a user interface, for creating predefined or custom speech commands.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The performance of speech recognition systems is usually evaluated in terms of accuracy and speed.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Accuracy is usually rated with word error rate (WER), whereas speed is measured in elapsed time.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Other measures of accuracy include Single Word Error Rate (SWER) and Command Success Rate (CSR).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Speech recognition is complicated by many properties of speech.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Vocalizations vary in terms of accent, pronunciation, articulation, roughness, dialect, nasality, pitch, volume, and speed.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Speech is distorted by background noise, echoes, and recording characteristics.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] e.g. the 10 digits "zero" to "nine" can be recognized essentially perfectly, but vocabulary sizes of 200, 5000, or 100000 may have error rates of 3%, 7%, or 45% respectively.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] are difficult to discriminate because they are confusing words (most notoriously, the E-set: "B, C, D, E, G, P, T, V, Z (when "Z" is pronounced "zee" rather than "zed", depending on region); an 8% error rate is considered good for this vocabulary.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Speech recognition is a multi-level pattern recognition task.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] This hierarchy of constraints improves accuracy.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] By combining decisions probabilistically at all lower levels, and making ultimate decisions only at the highest level, speech recognition is broken into several phases.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Computationally, it is a problem in which a sound pattern has to be recognized or classified into a category that represents a meaning to a human.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Every acoustic signal can be broken into smaller sub-signals.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] As the more complex sound signal is divided, different levels are created, where at the top level are complex sounds made of simpler sounds on the lower level, etc.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] At the lowest level, simple and more probabilistic rules apply.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] These sounds are put together into more complex sounds on upper level, a new set of more deterministic rules predicts what the complex sound represents.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The upper level of a deterministic rule should figure out the meaning of complex expressions.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] In order to expand our knowledge about speech recognition, we need to take into consideration neural networks.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Sound is produced by air (or some other medium) vibration.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Sound creates a wave that has two measures: amplitude (strength), and frequency (vibrations per second).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Accuracy can be computed with the help of WER, which is calculated by aligning the recognized word and referenced word using dynamic string alignment.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The problem may occur while computing the WER due to the difference between the sequence lengths of the recognized word and referenced word.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] where *s* is the number of substitutions, *d* is the number of deletions, *i* is the number of insertions, and *n* is the number of word references.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] While computing, the word recognition rate (WRR) is used.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Speech recognition can become a means of attack, theft, or accidental operation.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] For example, activation words like "Alexa" spoken in an audio or video broadcast can cause devices in homes and offices to start listening for input inappropriately, or possibly take an unwanted action.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Voice-controlled devices may be accessible to unauthorized users.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Attackers may be able to gain access to personal information, like calendars, address book contents, private messages, and documents.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] They may also be able to impersonate the user to send messages or make online purchases.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Two attacks have been demonstrated that use artificial sounds.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] One transmits ultrasound and attempts to send commands without people noticing.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The other adds small, inaudible distortions to other speech or music that are specially crafted to confuse the specific speech recognition system into recognizing music as speech, or to make what sounds like one command to a human sound like a different command to the system.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Regular conferences include SpeechTEK and SpeechTEK Europe, ICASSP, Interspeech/Eurospeech, and the IEEE ASRU.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] Conferences in the field of natural language processing, such as ACL, NAACL, EMNLP, and HLT, include papers on speech processing.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The main journal is *IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech and Language Processing*.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/speech-recognition] The largest speech recognition-related project ongoing as of 2007 was the GALE project, which involves both speech recognition and translation components.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] It is capable of transcribing speech in English and multiple other languages, and can translate several non-English languages into English.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Whisper is a weakly-supervised deep learning acoustic model, made using an encoder-decoder transformer architecture.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] OpenAI claims that the combination of different training data and post-training filtering used in its development has led to improved recognition of accents, background noise, and jargon compared to previous approaches.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] While the model does not outperform larger, more specialized models and still experiences AI hallucination, it has been showed to be useful for general sound recognition and has many applications across different industries.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Speech recognition has had a long history in research; the first approaches made use of statistical methods, such as dynamic time warping, and later hidden Markov models.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] At around the 2010s, deep neural network approaches became more common for speech recognition models, which were enabled by the availability of large datasets ("big data") and increased computational performance.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Transformers, introduced in 2017 by Google, displaced many prior state-of-the-art approaches across a wide range in machine learning, and started becoming the core neural architecture in fields such as language modeling and computer vision.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Weakly-supervised approaches to training acoustic models were recognized in the early 2020s as promising for speech recognition approaches using deep neural networks.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] According to a NYT report, in 2021 OpenAI believed they exhausted sources of higher-quality data to train their large language models and decided to complement scraped web text with transcriptions of YouTube videos and podcasts, and developed Whisper to solve this task.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Whisper Large V2 was released on December 8, 2022, followed by Whisper Large V3 being released in November 2023, during the OpenAI Dev Day.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] In March 2025, OpenAI released new transcription models based on GPT-4o and GPT-4o mini, both of which have lower error rates than Whisper.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The Whisper architecture is based on an encoder-decoder transformer.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Input audio is resampled to 16,000 Hertz (Hz) and converted to an 80-channel Log-magnitude Mel spectrogram using 25 ms windows with a 10 ms stride.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The spectrogram is then normalized to a [-1, 1] range with near-zero mean.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The encoder takes this Mel spectrogram as input and processes it.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] It first passes through two convolutional layers.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Sinusoidal positional embeddings are added.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] It is then processed by a series of Transformer encoder blocks (with pre-activation residual connections).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The encoder's output is layer normalized.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The decoder is a standard transformer decoder.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] It has the same width and Transformer blocks as the encoder.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] It uses learned positional embeddings and tied input-output token representations (using the same weight matrix for both the input and output embeddings).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] It uses a byte-pair encoding tokenizer, of the same kind as used in GPT-2.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] English-only models use the GPT-2 vocabulary, while multilingual models employ a re-trained multilingual vocabulary with the same number of words.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The training dataset consists of 680,000 hours of labeled audio-transcript pairs sourced from the internet using semi-supervised learning.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] This includes 117,000 hours in 96 non-English languages and 125,000 hours of X→English translation data, where X stands for any non-English language.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Speechless segments were also included to allow voice activity detection training.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] For the files still remaining after the filtering process, audio files were then broken into 30-second segments paired with the subset of the transcript that occurs within that time.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] If this predicted spoken language differed from the language of the text transcript associated with the audio, that audio-transcript pair was not used for training the speech recognition models, but instead for training translation.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The model was trained using the AdamW optimizer with gradient norm clipping and a linear learning rate decay with warmup, with batch size 256 segments.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Training proceeded for 1 million updates (approximately 2-3 epochs).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] No data augmentation or regularization, except for the Large V2 model, which used SpecAugment, Stochastic Depth, and BPE Dropout.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The training used data parallelism with float16, dynamic loss scaling, and activation checkpointing.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] After training the first model, researchers ran it on different subsets of the training data, each representing a distinct source.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Data sources were ranked by a combination of their error rate and size.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Manual inspection of the top-ranked sources (high error, large size) helped determine if the source was low quality (e.g., partial transcriptions, inaccurate alignment).
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] After training, it was fine-tuned to suppress the prediction of speaker names and low-quality sources were then removed.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] While Whisper does not outperform models which specialize in the LibriSpeech dataset, when tested across many datasets, it is more robust and makes 55.2% fewer errors than other models.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Whisper has a differing error rate with respect to transcribing different languages, with a higher word error rate in languages not well-represented in the training data.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The authors found that multi-task learning improved overall performance compared to models specialized to one task.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] They conjectured that the best Whisper model trained is still underfitting the dataset, and larger models and longer training can result in better models.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Third-party evaluations have found varying levels of AI hallucination.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] A study of transcripts of public meetings found hallucinations in eight out of every 10 transcripts, while an engineer discovered hallucinations in "about half" of 100 hours of transcriptions and a developer identified them in "nearly every one" of 26,000 transcripts.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] A study of 13,140 short audio segments (averaging 10 seconds) found 187 hallucinations (1.4%), 38% of which generated text that could be harmful because it inserted false references to things like race, non-existent medications, or violent events that were not in the audio.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The model has been used as the base for many applications, such as a unified model for speech recognition and more general sound recognition.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Whisper has also been integrated into the workflow of biomedical research.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] In 2025, a study on Alzheimer's disease detection used the model to transcribe spontaneous speech recordings.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The transcripts that were generated by the model were combined with LLM vector embeddings and traditional classifiers to help classify the patients' health.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] Another application is when OVALYTICS incorporated Whisper to transcribe YouTube videos and automate content moderation systems, which improved its detection of offensive content.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] The model has also been used in academic libraries and cultral heritage institutions to generate transcripts and captions for their digitized audiovisual collections.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] In a 2025 case study, Emory University Libraries found that Whisper reduced the labor used in transcription by around 30-35%, shifting work from text creation to text correction.
[src:speech-recognition-ml/whisper-speech-recognition-system] However, human review is still necessary to make sure accuracy, formatting, and accessibility are all standard.
